I would recommend loading the XML as a DOMdocument and then using Xpaths to get this data from the XML. Like so:

	$doc = new DOMDocument();
    $doc-&gt;loadXML($xmlstring, LIBXML_NOERROR);
    $petFriendlyNodes = getPetFriendlyValue($doc);

    function getPetFriendlyValue($doc)  { 
        $query = &quot;//property/propertyvariables/propertyvariable[@id=&#39;variableID61849&#39;]/variablevalue/text()&quot;;
        $xpath = new DOMXPath($doc);
        //print_r( $xpath-&gt;evaluate($query)[0]);
        return $xpath-&gt;evaluate(query)[0]
    }

This returns the first object that matches the Xpath list:

    DOMText Object
    (
        [wholeText] =&gt; 1
        [data] =&gt; 1
        [length] =&gt; 1
        [nodeName] =&gt; #text
        [nodeValue] =&gt; 1
        [nodeType] =&gt; 3
        [parentNode] =&gt; (object value omitted)
        [childNodes] =&gt; 
        [firstChild] =&gt; 
        [lastChild] =&gt; 
        [previousSibling] =&gt; 
        [nextSibling] =&gt; 
        [attributes] =&gt; 
        [ownerDocument] =&gt; (object value omitted)
        [namespaceURI] =&gt; 
        [prefix] =&gt; 
        [localName] =&gt; 
        [baseURI] =&gt; [...]
        [textContent] =&gt; 1
    )


This does assume that the variable ID is always the same. You can of course decide to return more or different parts of the node

Using SimpleXML, you can easily use XPath to check for the Pet Friendly variable (assuming this is a constant - which I would expect it to be).  Then if either the value isn&#39;t found or it&#39;s 0, set it to `no` otherwise set it to `yes`...

    $properties = $xml-&gt;property;
    $petfriendly = $properties-&gt;xpath(&quot;//propertyvariable[@id=&#39;variableID61849&#39;]/variablevalue&quot;);
    if ( count($petfriendly) == 0 || $petfriendly[0] == &#39;0&#39; ){
        $property_meta[&#39;petfriendly&#39;] = &#39;no&#39;;
    }
    else {
        $property_meta[&#39;petfriendly&#39;] = &#39;yes&#39;;
    }

